entry.title: Philippines reopens its skies to incoming international flights

media:group.media:title: Philippines reopens its skies to incoming international flights
media:group.media:description:
International flights can land in the Philippine capital again after the government reopened its airport. Flights were stopped last week after the country could not cope with thousands of workers returning from overseas. There have been more than 10,000 confirmed cases and 700 deaths in the country. Al Jazeera's Jamela Alindogan reports from Manila, Philippines.

entry.title: Will the global tourism industry survive the pandemic? I Inside Story

media:group.media:title: Will the global tourism industry survive the pandemic? I Inside Story
media:group.media:description:
The global tourism industry has all but ground to a halt because of the coronavirus pandemic. Most international flights have stopped and hotel bookings evaporated as countries closed their borders and imposed lockdowns. That's put a hundred million jobs at risk, according to the UN's World Tourism Organization. However, countries with falling infection rates are now planning to ease some of those restrictions. They plan to encourage travellers and their cash to venture abroad again. So what's the future of the tourism industry?
Presenter: Bernard Smith
Guests:
Kimarli Fernando - Head of Sri Lanka's National Tourism Development Authority.
George Papaconstantinou - Former Greek Minister of Finance and Professor at the European University Institute School of Transnational Governance.
Virginia Messina - Managing Director of the World Travel and Tourism Council.

entry.title: Coronavirus: What do pregnant women need to know? | The Stream

media:group.media:title: Coronavirus: What do pregnant women need to know? | The Stream
media:group.media:description:
The coronavirus pandemic is causing extra stress for many expectant mothers around the world.
One major reason for this is because health experts "are operating in a data-free zone" when it comes to pregnant women and COVID-19. Research is still pending on whether these women are more susceptible to catching the illness, and if contracting the virus could affect fetal health.
Compounding this fear of the unknown are strict social distancing guidelines. This has caused increased mental distress for women who are deprived of the support of loved ones and those who could benefit from helpful birthing and breastfeeding classes.
From a medical perspective, pre- and post-natal treatments are rapidly evolving to ensure the safest care. In some nations, regular checkups have moved online to prevent unnecessary hospital visits. In these instances, expectant mothers are taught to monitor fetal heartbeats and their own blood pressure - a change that may stick around for years to come.
In this episode we ask, what do pregnant women need to know about the coronavirus?

entry.title: Canadian truck drivers face new risks

entry.title: Iran missile 'accidentally' strikes own ship, kills one sailor

media:group.media:title: Iran missile 'accidentally' strikes own ship, kills one sailor
media:group.media:description:
An Iranian missile fired during a training exercise in the Gulf of Oman has struck a support vessel near its target, killing at least one sailor and wounding several others, according to Iranian media. The friendly fire incident happened on Sunday near the port of Jask, some 1,270 kilometres (790 miles) southeast of Tehran on the Gulf of Oman, Iranian state TV said on Monday, citing the Iranian navy. There are fears dozens of people could be dead.
Al Jazeera’s Zein Basravi reports live from Tehran.

entry.title: Saudi Arabia announces new austerity drive

media:group.media:title: Saudi Arabia announces new austerity drive
media:group.media:description:
Saudi Arabia has announced tough new austerity measures aimed at shoring up state finances which have been battered by low oil prices and the coronavirus pandemic. From July 1, it will raise its Value Added Tax from 5 to 15 percent and suspend a cost of living allowance for workers.
To discuss the effect of these moves, Al Jazeera spoke to Ali AlAhmed via Skype from Washington, DC, in the US. He is the director of the Institute for Gulf Affairs

entry.title: Hundreds gather in Baghdad in new round of anti-gov't protests

media:group.media:title: Hundreds gather in Baghdad in new round of anti-gov't protests
media:group.media:description:
Hundreds of Iraqis have returned to the streets after weeks of a coronavirus lockdown, demanding sweeping political and economic reforms, just days following the swearing-in of a new government. Iraqi's Prime Minister Mustafa al-Kadhimi promised to set free protesters arrested in demonstrations which started in October 2019. But the protesters say systemic change is needed.
Al Jazeera’s Simona Foltyn reports from Baghdad, Iraq.

entry.title: UK's Johnson says shops, schools could partially reopen from June

media:group.media:title: UK's Johnson says shops, schools could partially reopen from June
media:group.media:description:

entry.title: UK's Johnson delivers new guidance in COVID-19 speech

media:group.media:title: UK's Johnson delivers new guidance in COVID-19 speech
media:group.media:description:
United Kingdom Prime Minister Boris Johnson has addressed the nation, providing new guidance on dealing with the coronavirus lockdown. The UK has recorded nearly 32,000 deaths, the most in Europe and the second-highest pandemic toll worldwide. Ahead of the prime minister's speech, the government was accused of confusing the public with a new "stay alert" message, which replaces the earlier "stay at home" slogan. Kevin Craig, the chief executive officer of Political Lobbying and Media Relations Ltd (PLMR), a political communications agency in the UK, talks to Al Jazeera.
